observations.recommendation:
We recommend that Management:
a. Oblige the inventory committee to regularly conduct a physical count of all PPEs and to reconcile the results of the count with the property and accounting records;
b. Require the MAccO and the MTO to ensure that property records are reconciled with the accounting records to come up with a reliable PPE account balance in the financial statements;
c. Direct the MTO and the MAccO to maintain updated property/ledger cards for the other PPEs to facilitate reconciliation of their records and immediate verification of discrepancies;
d. Exert utmost efforts to locate the unaccounted PPE with an aggregate cost amounting to ₱3,510,235.31; and,
e. Conduct a one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts of the Municipality be conducted in strict compliance with the guidelines and procedures set under COA Circular 2020-006 to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

We recommended the Management to:
1
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit to the bank and to the audit team the Monthly Bank Reconciliation Statement of all bank accounts within the period prescribed in COA Circular No. 96-011; 
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to regularly draw journal vouchers to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment and correction in the GL within the period prescribed to present the correct balance of the CIB account in the financial statements at any balance sheet date; 
c. Fill-up vacant positions, if any, or create plantilla positions for additional staff for the accounting office through a Sangguniang Bayan Resolution to augment the existing workforce; and 
d. Close, thru a SB Resolution, all accounts under special trust fund for which the purpose of its creation cease to exist due to completion of programs related thereto, and transfer the existing balance of the said accounts to the general fund to prevent incurrence of unnecessary bank charges and minimize number of accounts being maintained that require preparation of BRS.

We recommended the Management to:
a. Require the Treasury Office/GSO to submit the SSMI of the supplies issued to end-users costing P4.075 million to the accounting office supported with RISs and henceforth, prepare and submit the SSMI report to the Accounting Office on a weekly basis; 
b. Instruct the Accountant to maintain Ledger Cards and to compute the inventory costs using the Moving Average Cost, or the unit cost from its latest purchase, if moving average cost per unit cannot be determined; 
c. Direct the Accountant and the GSO to reconcile their records regularly to establish correct inventory account balances, if any; and, 
d. Create an Inventory Committee to regularly conduct physical count of supplies and materials and submit a copy of the inventory report to the accounting office, copy furnished the Audit Team.

We recommended the Management to:
a. Create an inventory committee to regularly conduct a physical count of PPEs and submit the RPCPPE to the MAccO, copy furnished the Audit Team; 
b. Require the MAccO to create subsidiary ledgers of all the PPE accounts in its eNGAS based on the RPCPPE prepared by the inventory committee and to ensure that the accounting records are reconciled with property records to come up with a reliable PPE account balance in the financial statements; 
c. Direct the MTO to maintain updated and complete property cards to facilitate reconciliation of the property and accounting records and immediate verification of discrepancies; and, 
d. Account for missing property items, if any.

We recommended the Management to:
a. Re-assess the necessity of pursuing the unimplemented projects, otherwise, reprogram the same to developmental projects that suit the present needs of the community; 
b. Conduct proper validation of identified or proposed projects to ensure that only feasible PPAs, free from any issues of ownership and right-of-way, are included in the AIP; 
c. Consider bidding out those projects that were programmed to be clustered and implemented by Administration; and 
d. Hire/employ casual employees or job order workers to assist in the preparation of programs of work and supervision of projects pursuant to Section 77 of the Local Government Code of 1991.

We recommended the following:
 Management to submit justification why the transaction should not be disallowed for being irregular since the documents showed that appropriation of prior year was used to obligate a transaction of a current year contrary to Section 350 of RA 7160;
The Head of the Requesting Unit shall ensure that ObR and DV are supported with valid and proper supporting documents before certifying to the necessity and legality of charges to appropriation and allotment under his direct supervision;
The Municipal Accountant, as the person in charge of the internal audit services of the Municipality, shall check on the completeness of the supporting documents before signing in the obligation and allotment box in the DV.

We recommended the following:
a. Management to submit justification why the transaction should not be disallowed for being irregular since the documents showed that appropriation of prior year was used to obligate a transaction of a current year contrary to Section 350 of RA 7160;
b. The Head of the Requesting Unit shall ensure that ObR and DV are supported with valid and proper supporting documents before certifying to the necessity and legality of charges to appropriation and allotment under his direct supervision;
c. The Municipal Accountant, as the person in charge of the internal audit services of the Municipality, shall check on the completeness of the supporting documents before signing in the obligation and allotment box in the DV.

We have recommended that the following measures be implemented:
Use the PCF only for non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses of not exceeding P1,000.00 for each PCV;
Return the unused balance of PCF at the end of the year and set up a new cash advance for PCF at the start of the ensuing year.
Pay regular and recurring expenses such as traveling expenses, diesel/gasoline expenses, annual dues to associations, meals and snacks, hire of musical instruments, and t-shirt printing through checks;
Consider reducing the amount of petty cash fund to a reasonable and appropriate amount sufficient for the non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses of the municipality for one month; and
Record the replenishment of the PCF in the amount of P94,080.88.
